<br>
1) The blade penetrates perpendicular to the hand between the metacarpal bones for the index and middle finger. This could leave an exit wound that cuts through the 'life line' on the palm at about a 20 degree angle. This would likely leave the index and middle fingers rather weak, although things could be held in the hand because the thumb isn't involved. The problem is that a 2 inch wound like this would likely split the palm all the way up to the crux between the fingers (quite nasty) unless the cut was all whe way down to where the two bones meet.<br>
<br>
2) The blade penetrates at an angle to the hand, cutting just to the thumb side of the index finger metacarpal. (Hold your hand with fingers extended but not spread, and turn the thumb toward you until you see no daylight between your fingers. This would be the angle.) this would cut more parallel to the 'life line', but would assuredly split the palm and nearly remove the thumb completely, rendering the hand mostly useless.<br>
<br>
Either of these wounds would be more manageable if the blade making the cut was thinner, more like a saber or rapier than a longsword (c. 1 inch or so). Hope this helps. <p>- - -<br>
