<br>
What was baffling to me, though, was how a character in a fantasy world would even <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>have</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> scars, considering the nature of magic and healing (which kind of does an end-run around medical science anyway, but hey, that's fantasy for ya <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) Here's how I handled it with my character.<br>
<br>
When my character got his scar he was just a boy.  He was running from a High Elf Paladin, who stabbed him with an enchanted sword.  The very nature of the blade, coupled with the zeal behind it, left scars on my character that he'll probably carry the rest of his life.  It's a powerful reminder of what the so-called &quot;good&quot; races are really capable of...<br>
<br>
The kind of wound my character endured would be fatal nine times out of ten.  Thanks to the magic of a fantasy realm, however, he survived and is now out adventuring 'n' stuff.  Basically, my opinion is, a lot of what happens in a fantasy realm is A) circumstantial and B) based heavily on the player behind the character, and the story they wish to tell.<br>
<br>
So if it suits your character's story to bear a scar, bear it!  And don't hesitate to tell the story behind it in whatever way works best for your character... it is, after all, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>your</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> character. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
